  <section>
    <h2>About the app</h2>
    <p>
      WhatCable reads USB-C cable and port data from the IOKit registry using Apple's
      public APIs. No root access, no SIP changes, no private entitlements. It shows
      charging speed, data rate, Thunderbolt and USB4 support, display bandwidth, and
      e-marker data, and it identifies where the bottleneck is: the Mac port, the cable,
      or the device on the other end.
    </p>
    <p>
      It doesn't just report what a cable claims about itself. It checks the cable's
      e-marker against what the connection actually negotiated, and on Thunderbolt links,
      against the controller's own independent hardware measurement of the link speed. So
      it catches a cable that fails to deliver, and corrects one that under-reports. It is
      not a physical cable tester and doesn't claim to be. Software can't see inside the
      jacket, only read what the hardware reports.
    </p>
    <p>
      No tracking, no telemetry, no background uploads. Free and open source (MIT licence),
      with <a href="https://github.com/darrylmorley/whatcable/stargazers" rel="noopener"><span data-gh-stars>7.5k</span> stars on GitHub</a>.
      Available as a direct download or via Homebrew cask, with a bundled command-line tool
      for scripting and JSON output. Interface and diagnostic verdicts translated into 19
      languages. Optional Pro tier at £9.99 one-time, one key covers two Macs. Requires
      Apple Silicon and macOS 14 or later.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>About the developer</h2>
    <p>
      Darryl Morley is a self-taught developer based in the UK. He works in e-commerce
      by day and builds Mac software in his spare time under Bitmoor Ltd. WhatCable started
      as a tool to answer a question he kept asking himself, which of these identical-looking
      cables actually does the thing, and turned into something other people wanted too.
    </p>
